The surface charge of the ZnFe2O4@Cys@NGQDs nano-carriers were obtained from ZP and the corresponding results are illustrated in Fig. 5
                        (a, b). The surface of ZnFe2O4@Cysteine nanocomposites was grafted with biocompatible NGQDs, to enhance their stability in physiological media and the product was referred to as ZnFe2O4@Cys@NGQDs [57]. The series changes on ZP of each sample at two pH (5.5 and 7.4) indicate the stepwise formation of ZnFe2O4@Cysteine@NGQDs nano-carriers (Fig. 5a, b). Coating the surface of ZnFe2O4 NPs with Cys@NGQDs creates functional surface groups including –OH, –SH, –COOH and − NH2. Cancer cell walls have a negative surface charge. When the pH of the nanocarrier changes from 7.4 to 5.5, its surface changes from negative (ZP = -31.9) to positive (ZP= +27.5) due to the protonation of functional groups, which causes its absorption in cancer cells. So, the surface coating of ferrite nanoparticles causes a targeted change in the surface charge of the nanocarrier with changing pH from 7.4 (normal cells) to 5.5 (cancer cells), which ultimately leads to the release of Cur in cancerous tissues and reduces the side effects of chemotherapy (Scheme 1
                        ). Especially, these surface-modified ZnFe2O4@Cys@NGQDs nano-carriers feature shows high colloidal stability in physiological conditions [58]. The colloidal stability of ZnFe2O4, ZnFe2O4@Cys and ZnFe2O4@Cys@NGQDs in physiological conditions, similar to the cancer physiological conditions, showed in Fig S2, which shows that the surface modification of ZnFe2O4 with Cys and NGQD leads to a decrease in aggregation and consequently the hydrodynamic diameter. The high accumulation of ZnFe2O4@Cys@NGQDs-Cur in cancerous tumors can be attributed to: 1) The interaction of Cys@NGQDs with tumor cells; and 2) EPR effect arising from the nano-size of carriers (Scheme 1). At pH 7.4, ZnFe2O4@Cys@NGQDs nano-carriers have negative surface charge (ZP = -31.9) and exhibits protein-resistant property for long blood circulation. Thus, with the decrease of pH value (to pH 5.5), it gradually transfers to positive surface charge (ZP= +27.5) and shows enhanced interaction with protein, which could improve its cell adhesion, internalization and Cur release (pH 5.5) (Scheme 1) [59].

One of the limitations of SDT using US is the low activity of radical production, ferrites with high ability to produce radicals can be used here as a group of suitable compounds. For this purpose, ZnFe2O4-based NSSs were used here as NSSs for increasing the sonocatalytic efficiency. To further increase the sonocatalytic efficiency, ZnFe2O4 NSSs were combined with 0D NGQDs [71]. Carbon in the structure of ZnFe2O4@NGQDs nanocomposites transfers and traps electrons excited from the conduction band of ZnFe2O4 NSSs. The incorporated NGQDs with ZnFe2O4 NSSs can help effectively inhibit the recombination of e−/h+ pairs, enhancing the charge carrier lifetime and the subsequent formation of a more strong oxidizing radicals (scheme 2
                     ), like singlet oxygen, as well as superoxide and hydroxyl radicals. The increase in the separation and longer lifetime of the e− and h+ pairs were the main reasons behind the synergy between NGQDs and ZnFe2O4 
                     [72,73]. The ROS generated from ZnFe2O4@Cys@NGQDs-Cur nano-carriers by US irradiation and the release of Cur at specific sites lead to synergistic effect of sonodynamic and chemotherapy [74]. The ROS details are listed in Supplementary Material text Fig S1. US irradiation could be increased membrane permeability and intracellular uptake of the chemotherapeutic agent (Cur) [75]. The surface of ZnFe2O4 NSSs was also modified with biocompatible Cys to increase the stability of colloidal ZnFe2O4@Cys@NGQDs under physiological conditions (Fig. 2S). The so-called enhanced EPR effect (scheme1) allows the nano-carriers to simply move through the blood vessels and accumulate in the target tumor tissue [76]. After sequential US irradiations and Cur release, pH-responsive ZnFe2O4@Cys@NGQDs-Cur nano-carriers embark on the generation of intracellular ROS and release of Cur which attack the cancer cells in weakly acidic intracellular and/or lysosomal environment of the tumor (pH 5.5) (scheme 2) by inhibiting the replication of their DNA. The developed probe constitutes a novel pathway for enhanced ROS treatments [77]. Finally, ZnFe2O4@Cys@NGQDs-Cur together with pH/ROS treatment were more effective due to the synergistic therapeutic effect of the specific release of drug through pH/US-stimuli.
